# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: livy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The work covers the period from the legends concerning the arrival of Aeneas and the refugees from the fall of Troy, to the city's founding in 753 BC, the expulsion of the Kings in 509 BC, and down to Livy's own time, during the reign of the emperor Augustus.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The last event covered by Livy is the death of Drusus in 9 BC.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] 35 of 142 books, about a quarter of the work, are still extant.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The surviving books deal with the events down to 293 BC (books 1–10), and from 219 to 166 BC (books 21–45).
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The *History of Rome* originally comprised 142 "books", 35 of which—Books 1–10 with the Preface and Books 21–45—still exist in reasonably complete form.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Damage to a manuscript of the 5th century resulted in large gaps (*lacunae*) in Books 41 and 43–45 (small lacunae exist elsewhere); that is, the material is not covered in any source of Livy's text.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Some passages are nevertheless known thanks to quotes from ancient authors, the most famous being on the death of Cicero, quoted by Seneca the Elder.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy was abridged, in antiquity, to an epitome, which survives for Book 1, but was itself abridged in the fourth century into the so-called *Periochae*, which is simply a list of contents.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The *Periochae* survive for the entire work, except for books 136 and 137.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] In Oxyrhynchus, a similar summary of books 37–40, 47–55, and only small fragments of 88 was found on a roll of papyrus that is now in the British Museum classified as P.Oxy.IV 0668.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] There is another fragment, named P.Oxy.XI 1379, which represents a passage from the first book (I, 6) and that shows a high level of correctness.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] However, the Oxyrhynchus Epitome is damaged and incomplete.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy wrote in a mixture of annual chronology and narrative.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] This emerged from his decision to organise his narrative on a year-by-year scheme with regular announcements of elections of "consuls, prodigies, temple dedications, triumphs, and the like".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] This kind of year-by-year list of events is termed "annalistic history".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy employed annalistic features to associate his history with the dominant traditional of Roman history, which was to write these annalistic chronicles; in so doing, he "imbued his history with an aura of continuity and stability" along with "pontifical authority".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The first and third decades (see below) of Livy's work are written so well that Livy has become a *sine qua non* of curricula in Golden Age Latin.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Some have argued that subsequently the quality of his writing began to decline, and that he becomes repetitious and wordy.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] However, Livy also employed repetitive and formulaic wording in description of repetitive military affairs, described by Ogilvie as "mechanical and careless".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Modern readers, however, view Livy's repetitive prose more positively at least in performance of prayers, blessings, and public religious rituals.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] A digression in Book 9, Sections 17–19, suggests that the Romans would have beaten Alexander the Great if he had lived longer and had turned west to attack the Romans, making this digression one of the oldest known written alternate history scenarios.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The first five books were published between 27 and 25 BC.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The first date mentioned is the year Augustus received that eponymous title: twice in the first five books Livy uses it.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] For the second date, Livy lists the closings of the temple of Janus but omits that of 25 (it had not happened yet).
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy continued to work on the *History* for much of the rest of his life, publishing new material by popular demand.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] This explains why the work falls naturally into 12 packets, mainly groups of 10 books, or decades, sometimes of 5 books (pentads or pentades) and the rest without any packet order.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The scheme of dividing it entirely into decades is a later innovation of copyists.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The second pentad did not come out until 9 or after, some 16 years after the first pentad.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] In Book IX Livy states that the Cimminian Forest was more impassable than the German had been recently, referring to the Hercynian Forest (Black Forest) first opened by Drusus and Ahenobarbus.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] There is no uniform system of classifying and naming manuscripts.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Often the relationship of one manuscript (MS) to another remains unknown or changes as perceptions of the handwriting change.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy's release of chapters by packet diachronically encouraged copyists to copy by decade.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Each decade has its own conventions, which do not necessarily respect the conventions of any other decade.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] A family of MSS descend through copying from the same MSS (typically lost).
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] MSS vary widely; to produce an emendation or a printed edition was and is a major task.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Usually variant readings are given in footnotes.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] All of the manuscripts (except one) of the first ten books (first decade) of *Ab urbe condita*, which were copied through the Middle Ages and were used in the first printed editions, are derived from a single recension commissioned by Quintus Aurelius Symmachus, consul, AD 391.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] A recension is made by comparing extant manuscripts and producing a new version, an emendation, based on the text that seems best to the editor.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The latter then "subscribed" to the new MS by noting on it that he had emended it.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Symmachus, probably using the authority of his office, commissioned Tascius Victorianus to emend the first decade.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] This recension and family of descendant MSS is called the Nicomachean, after two of the subscribers.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Epigraphists go on to identify several hands and lines of descent.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] A second family of the first decade consists of the Verona Palimpsest, reconstructed and published by Theodore Mommsen, 1868; hence the Veronensis MSS.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] It includes 60 leaves of Livy fragments covering Books III-VI.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The handwriting style is dated to the 4th century, only a few centuries after Livy.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] During the Middle Ages, there were constant rumours that the complete books of the History of Livy lay hidden in the library of a Danish or German Monastery.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] One individual even affirmed under oath in the court of Martin V that he had seen the whole work, written in Lombardic script, in a monastery in Denmark.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] All of these rumours were later found to be unsubstantiated.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The orthodox view is that "Livy was a very poor historian indeed, whether by ancient or modern standards".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] He did "no primary research", relying "exclusively on earlier histories".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] His understanding of those sources was poor: with Livy relating the same event twice on multiple occasions.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Moreover, "there are clear signs that his Greek was not good enough to understand properly one of his major sources, the Greek historian Polybius", whom he followed closely for events in the east in books 31 to 45.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy also did not intend to produce a history in terms of cataloguing and understanding the past, but rather, in terms of preserving a "memory ... [that] equips the reader with a sense of wrong and right as determined or exemplified by the actions of one's predecessors".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Moreover, the work was also written "under the shadow of the new emperor" with the goal of supporting "the idea that the Augustan principate was the *culmination* of Roman history".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] While other sources have attempted to rehabilitate Livy's history in terms of its literary quality (for example, DS Levene's *Livy on the Hannibalic War*), this is not a defence of the history's historicity.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Modern criticism of Livy also goes into the "inaccuracy of his battle accounts, the vagueness of his geography, ... the excessive partiality shown to one or [an]other of his 'heroes', and in general the highly rhetorical nature of not only his speeches but also of his dramatic narrations".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The details of Livy's *History* vary from the legendary and mythical stories at the beginning to detailed accounts of real events toward the end.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy too recognised that the early years of Rome were profoundly ahistorical, saying "the traditions of what happened prior to the foundation of the city or whilst it was being built, are more fitted to adorn the creations of the poet than the authentic records of the historian".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The first book has been one of the most significant sources of the various accounts of the traditional legend of Romulus and Remus.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] However, when comparing Livy's account of the kingdom to that of Dionysius of Halicarnassus, his scepticism is better evident, as he omitted "many stories which seemed rather improbable to him".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] And in general, the early parts of the books are important accounts of early Rome surviving from antiquity.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy's treatment of his own sources was more in terms of arranging material and synthesising a narrative rather than engaging in original research into official documents; in doing so, he "did little more than [trying] to reconcile discrepancies in his sources by using arguments from probability".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] However, Livy did not substantially grapple with the possibility that annalists knew how to invent probable stories.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Furthermore, rarely did Livy provide the names of his sources, especially in the long passages where he followed one major source with infrequent comparisons to other sources to correct errors.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Fortunately, Livy's goal in telling existing narratives with "better style and arrangement" means he seemingly did not introduce into his history "invented episodes of exaggerations".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy's work "came at the end of a long line of historians ... conventionally known as the 'annalistic tradition'".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Where he relied on these sources (along with other narrative sources available in his day) his principle was similar to that of Herodotus': "tell what he had been told".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Roman historiography goes back to Quintus Fabius Pictor who wrote c.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] 200 BC, heavily influenced by Greek historiographical canons and methods.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Other annalists included Quintus Ennius, Marcius Porcius Cato the censor, Lucius Calpurnius Piso Frugi, Lucius Cassius Hemina, Gnaeus Gellius, Vennonius, Valerius Antias, Licinius Macer, Quintus Claudius Quadrigarius, and Quintus Aelius Tubero.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The last three annalists (operating in the first century BC) are, however, "widely believed to have been less scrupulous than their second-century predecessors", supplying stories about the archaic period "from their own imaginations".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] However, as to certain elements of his narrative, Livy may have relied on "unscrupulous annalists" who "did not hesitate to invent a series of face-saving victories".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Livy did not use the *libri lintei* or the *annales maximi* kept by the pontifex maximus; nor did he "walk around in Rome, or elsewhere, to discover inscriptions or other new documents".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The difficulties of using the senate's own archives, documented in speeches by Cicero, "hint... at the possibilities of falsifying evidence" and the poor transmission of authoritative historical records.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Niccolò Machiavelli's work on republics, *Discourses on Livy*, is presented as a commentary on the *History of Rome*.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The first complete rendering of *Ab urbe condita* into English was Philemon Holland's translation published in 1600.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] According to Considine, "it was a work of great importance, presented in a grand folio volume of 1,458 pages, and dedicated to [Queen Elizabeth I]".
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] A notable translation of Livy titled *History of Rome* was made by B.O.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] Foster in 1919 for the Loeb Classical Library.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] A partial translation by Aubrey de Sélincourt was printed in 1960–1965 for Penguin Classics.
[src:livy/ab-urbe-condita-libri-livy] The version of Livy available on Wikisource is that from the 1905 translation of Reverend Canon Roberts for Everyman's Library.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] The firm was founded in 1807 by Charles and Adam Black in Edinburgh.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] In 1851, the company purchased the copyrights to Sir Walter Scott's *Waverly* novels for £27,000.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] The company moved to the Soho district of London in 1889.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] During the years 1827–1903 the firm published the seventh, eighth and ninth editions of the *Encyclopædia Britannica*.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] This was purchased from Archibald Constable after his company's failure to publish the seventh edition of the encyclopedia.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] Adam Black retired in 1870 due to his disapproval of his sons' extravagant plans for its ninth edition.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] This edition, however, would sell half a million sets and was released in 24 volumes from 1875 to 1889.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] Beginning in 1839, the firm published a series of travel guides known as *Black's Guides*.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] The company was the publisher of the annual *Who's Who* (since 1849) and also, since 2002, the *Whitaker's Almanack*.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] Other notable works include *Black's Medical Dictionary* and the *Know The Game* series of sports rules and laws reference books.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] Black Colour Books: Twenty Shilling Series* (1901–21), a "range of high-quality colour collectable picture books" which are still collected by bibliophiles.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] Wodehouse's first book, *The Pothunters*, and went on to produce many of his early works.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] In 1989 A & C Black purchased both Christopher Helm Publishers and later the Pica Press, publishers of the Helm Identification Guides, from Christopher Helm.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] In 2000 A & C Black was purchased by Bloomsbury Publishing Plc, which continued producing the former's range of reference works.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] Poyser and their back-list of around 70 ornithology titles were acquired from Elsevier Science.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] A & C Black purchased Methuen Drama from Methuen Publishing in 2006, and acquired Arden Shakespeare from Cengage Learning in 2008.
[src:livy/adam-and-charles-black] In 2016, A & C Black Music list moved to Collins Learning, a division of HarperCollins Publishers Ltd.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] In contrast to modern adoption, Roman *adoptio* was neither designed nor intended to build emotionally satisfying families and support childrearing.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Among all social classes, childless couples or those who wanted to expand the size of their families instead might foster children.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Evidence is meager for the *adoptio* of young children for purposes other than securing a male heir, and probably would have been employed mostly by former slaves legitimating the status of their own children born into slavery or outside a legally valid marriage.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Roman women could own, inherit, and control property as citizens, and therefore could exercise prerogatives of the *paterfamilias* pertaining to ownership and inheritance.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] They played an increasingly significant role in succession and the inheritance of property from the 2nd century BC through the 2nd century AD, but as an instrument for transferring paternal *potestas*, adoption was mainly a male-gendered practice.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Formal adoption was practiced primarily for financial, social, and political purposes among the property-owning classes.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Free working people for whom these interests were minimal had little need of the cumbersome legal procedure and instead fostered if they wished to rear children.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] For the Romans, kinship was "biologically based but not biologically determined", and procedures such as adoption and divorce gave them greater latitude to restructure their families than was allowed in Christian Europe.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Cicero said that adoption was an accepted way to ensure the *hereditas* (transmission) of three aspects of Roman family continuity: the family name *(nomen)*, wealth *(pecunia)*, and religious rites *(sacra)*.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Adoption was appropriate for a man who had no legitimate children, but if there were already legitimate heirs, adoption risked diluting their inheritance and the social status that came with it.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Romans tended to prefer small families of two or three children for this reason, though premodern rates of neonatal and childhood mortality, along with other factors, could be an unsought brake on family size that jeopardized the family line.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] In adopting an adult heir, the father "could see what he was getting".
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Adoption was carried out by the male who was head of his family, the *paterfamilias*, and his adopting did not make his wife a mother.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Nor was marriage required; an adult bachelor could adopt in order to pass along his family name and *potestas*, as could a citizen eunuch (Latin *spado*).
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] A close relative was preferred as the adoptee, and a *paterfamilias* might adopt a grandson, especially if the grandson's father was not in the line of succession.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The grandson might be his daughter's son, or the *pater* might have removed the boy's father from succession by emancipating him.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] One common pattern in Roman adoption was for a woman's childless brother to adopt one of her sons.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] A brother or cousin on the father's side might relinquish *potestas* over a son to provide a childless man with an adoptive heir.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Adoption of a stepson from the wife's previous marriage was another strategy, if the stepson had no children; after adoption, his offspring would enter the line as grandchildren of the adopting *paterfamilias*.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The adoptee did not have to be a relative.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Romans placed a high value on the social bonds of friendship (*amicitia*), and a childless man might adopt a friend or friend's son.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Fostering was preferred to adopting children of "low" birth or unknown parentage, and in Roman Egypt it was unlawful to adopt a male foundling.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The *paterfamilias* generally transmitted his estate to an adoptee of his own rank, or the adoptee acquired the social rank of the adoptive family, with some exceptions.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Most often adoption would have been a lateral move or a modest boost to the adoptee's standing and wealth, but a freedman could also be adopted.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] A slave might even be simultaneously manumitted and adopted by his former master, who became both his patron *(patronus)* and his "father".
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The adoption of a freedman placed his property under the control of his new *paterfamilias*; it no longer belonged to him, but it would return to him along with the rest of his inheritance.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The choice of a freedman for adoption may have been motivated most often by gaining access to his resources rather than securing lineage.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] In the early Republic, a freedman through adoption gained the same status as the freeborn citizen who freed him.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] By the time of Tiberius, the adopted freedman was regarded as an unemancipated son in matters of family law but held only the rights of freedpersons otherwise.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Legislation that more closely regulated the varied statuses of *liberti* left the adoptee as a freedman who could not, for example, marry into the senatorial order even if he was adopted by a senator.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] In the late Republican era, Publius Clodius Pulcher famously subverted the usual course of "adopting up", surrendering his patrician status and becoming a nominal plebeian in order to qualify for the office of tribune.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Plebeians had adopted patricians before, but the reasons are not always clear and were not always political.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Cicero criticized the *adrogatio* of Clodius as solely politically motivated, and Clodius was emancipated immediately after he had achieved his aim.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Around the same time, a nominal adoption allowed Publius Cornelius Lentulus Spinther, son of the consul of 57 BC, to take a place in the College of Augurs by getting around the rule against having two members from the same *gens*.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The adoption seems to have been entirely fictional, since there is no evidence he ever made any use of the nomenclature of the Manlius Toquatus who adopted him.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Cicero's own patrician son-in-law, Publius Cornelius Dolabella, followed the path of Clodius in becoming a tribune by having himself adopted by a plebeian Cornelius.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Augustan legislation that granted privileges to fathers with multiple children and disadvantaged the childless also prompted adoptions of convenience.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Adoption for this purpose became enough of an issue that by the time of Nero a senatorial decree had tried to block legal dodges.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The historian Tacitus indicates that fictitious or "fake adoption" *(simulata adoptio)* could be detected by rapid emancipation once the benefit was realized – benefits including priority in the selection of provincial governors or candidates for office for men who had met the fatherhood quota.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The restrictions under the decree are not preserved in full, but a request for *adrogatio* could be denied if the would-be adoptive father already had children or was under the age of sixty and assumed able to procreate.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The development of *adrogatio* as a form of adoption is bound up with an early procedure for making a will that required the approval of the *comitia calata*, an assembly of the Roman people.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Upon the testator's death, the named heir was in effect adopted by the deceased.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The legislative act of adrogation was carried out by thirty magisterial lictors summoned by the Pontifex Maximus.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Because adoption law developed to support the particular institutions of Roman society, *adrogatio* could take place only in the city of Rome until the reign of Diocletian in the late third century.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Adrogation of female adoptees became possible through imperial rescript in the Antonine era (AD 138–192), and under exceptional circumstances a woman could adopt in the same way.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] In one documented case from the 3rd century, a woman whose sons had died was permitted to adopt her stepson.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Since a woman did not transfer paternal *potestas*, however, adoption accomplished little that could not be achieved through exercising her rights under inheritance law.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Testamentary adoption became more common during the late Republic.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Octavian, the future Augustus, was adopted in this way by his maternal great-uncle Julius Caesar.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Although *adoptio* was a practice aimed at furthering the succession of male privileges, both men and women could in effect "adopt" by passing along their property in a will with the condition that the heir carry on the family name *(condicio nominis ferendi)*.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The role of women in passing property along the family line became "increasingly important".
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Adoption was also the means by which married women could become part of their husband's family.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] From the late Republic through the Principate, most Roman women married *sine manu*, meaning that they remained part of their birth family and did not submit to their husband's *potestas*.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Livia, the wife of Augustus, outlived him, and only upon his death did testamentary adoption make her a part of the Julian family.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Illegitimacy does not appear to have carried much stigma in Roman society before the time of Constantine I, as many forms of Roman marriage existed, some rather loosely defined, along with quasi-marital unions such as *contubernium* among slaves and monogamous concubinage *(concubinatus)*.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Birth outside marriage was primarily at issue in matters of inheritance but was not a clearly defined status with debilities in law, as a principle of customary international law *(ius gentium)* was that a child took its status from the mother.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] A freedwoman whose male partner remained enslaved might find it advantageous to assert that her child was fatherless and not conceived during her own servitude, so as to ensure the child's freeborn status.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] It was unusual for freeborn persons to legitimate a child born outside a legally valid marriage, and typically a man would not adopt his illegitimate child unless he had no other heirs.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The adoptee could be *ingenuus* (freeborn) or a freedman, and might be a child resulting from *concubinatus*, though children were not especially desired from these unions.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Provisions for retroactive legitimation became more capacious in late antiquity as family law was adapted during the Christianization of the Roman Empire, in particular under Constantine and Justinian.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] In the Classical period, legitimation might have been more common among former slaves.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Since slaves lacked personhood under Roman law, they could neither contract a valid marriage nor institute an heir by means of a will.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] However, the quasi-marital union of *contubernium* was available to heterosexual slave couples with the owner's approval, and expressed an intent to marry if both parties gained rights of marriage and succession upon manumission.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Because a male slave did not possess the standing to assert patriarchal *potestas*, the child of an enslaved father was *spurius*, one whose father could not be legally identified as such—that is, illegitimate.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] If the father was later manumitted through a procedure that granted him full citizenship, he could legitimate his child through *adrogatio*.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Many Roman emperors came to power through adoption, either because their predecessors had no natural sons, or simply to ensure a smooth transition for the most capable candidate.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Augustus, as he was known after he became the first Roman emperor, was adopted into the *gens Julia* in the will of his great uncle, Julius Caesar.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] He inherited Caesar's money, name, and *auctoritas*.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] As Augustus's central role in the Principate solidified, it became increasingly important for him to designate an heir.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] He first adopted his daughter Julia's three sons by Marcus Agrippa, renaming them Gaius Caesar, Lucius Caesar, and Agrippa Caesar.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] After the former two died young and the latter was exiled, Augustus adopted his stepson, Tiberius Claudius Nero, on the condition that he adopt his own nephew, Germanicus (who was also Augustus's great nephew by blood).
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Tiberius succeeded Augustus, and after Tiberius's death, Germanicus's son Caligula became emperor.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Claudius adopted his stepson Lucius Domitius Ahenobarbus, who changed his name to Nero Claudius Caesar and succeeded Claudius as the emperor, Nero.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] The Nerva-Antonine dynasty was also united by a series of adoptions.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Nerva adopted the popular military leader Trajan.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Trajan in turn took Publius Aelius Hadrianus as his protégé and, although the legitimacy of the process is debatable, Hadrian claimed to have been adopted and took the name *Caesar Traianus Hadrianus* when he became emperor.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Hadrian adopted Lucius Ceionius Commodus, who changed his name to Lucius Aelius Caesar but predeceased Hadrian.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Hadrian then adopted Titus Aurelius Fulvus Boionius Arrius Antoninus, on condition that Antoninus in turn adopt both the natural son of the late Lucius Aelius and a promising young nephew of his wife.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] They ruled as Antoninus Pius, Lucius Verus and Marcus Aurelius respectively.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] This run of adoptive emperors came to an end when Marcus Aurelius named his biological son, Commodus, as his heir.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Adoption never became the official method of designating a successor, in part because Roman identity was based on citizenship with a visceral rejection of hereditary kingship.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] During the Principate, so called from Augustus's styling of himself as *princeps* (first among equals, in the manner of the *princeps senatus*), emperors consolidated their power by making use of the institutions of Republican Rome rather than overthrowing them outright.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] Augustus's early intentions seem to have been to apprentice and promote a successor on the basis of merit, but his longevity instead created an apparatus of centralized power from which his status as a private citizen could no longer be extricated.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] His fashioning of himself as "father of his country" enabled the transferral of his power over the Roman people in the same way that a *paterfamilias* of a family estate was bound to transfer his *potestas* whether or not the available successor was fully meritorious.
[src:livy/adoption-in-ancient-rome] A major transition in the means of imperial succession marks the periodization of Roman Imperial history into the Dominate, when Diocletian replaced adoption with the *consortium imperii*, designation of an heir by appointing him partner in *imperium*.
[src:livy/aedile] An **aedile** or **edile** (English: /ˈiːdʌɪl/ *EE-dighl*) was a magistrate in the Roman Republic who had responsibilities for the upkeep of the city, such as its buildings, roads, and markets; the availability of grain at reasonable prices; and the holding of games.
[src:livy/aedile] It also had some judicial functions, being able to issue fines and corporal punishments with an additional right to prosecute crimes before the assemblies, but by the middle republic was mostly an office used for distributing largesse to win the officeholder popular acclaim.
[src:livy/aedile] There were two kinds of aediles, plebeian aediles and curule aediles.
[src:livy/aedile] The former were, according to Roman tradition, the first aediles created (c.
[src:livy/aedile] 494 BC), initially as assistants to the plebeian tribunes, with the curule aediles created c.
[src:livy/aedile] The plebeian aediles, even though originally tribunician assistants, assimilated with the curule aediles: by the middle republic, aediles were junior to praetors and senior to quaestors, with the tribunate usually held *before* an aedilate.
[src:livy/aedile] The two types of aediles had largely the same duties.
[src:livy/aedile] The duties of the aediles did not long survive the republic.
[src:livy/aedile] While the office continued to exist under the empire, many of their public functions were assumed by the emperor or his appointees.
[src:livy/aedile] There were, however, aediles in self-governing communities outside of Rome who continued to be elected by and support their localities in much the same way the republican aediles at Rome did.
[src:livy/aedile] The Latin word for aedile, *aedilis*, is derived from the word *aedes* (meaning temple or dwelling place) with the suffix *-ilis*.
[src:livy/aedile] There were two kinds of aediles: curule and plebeian.
[src:livy/aedile] Curule aediles were elected in the tribal assembly, while plebeian aediles were elected in the plebeian council from plebeian candidates by a plebeian tribune.
[src:livy/aedile] While curule aediles possessed a curule chair, they did not possess *imperium* or the immunity from prosecution which it implied.
[src:livy/aedile] By the late middle republic the two pairs of aediles had largely overlapping duties in the upkeep of temples, markets, and streets.
[src:livy/aedile] They were also responsible for two major sets of annual games: the curule aediles held the *ludi Romani* and the Megalensian games; the plebeian aediles held the *ludi plebii* and the Floralian and Cerealian games.
[src:livy/aedile] Plebeian aediles also had responsibilities to keep plebeian records, which were likely stored at the Temple of Ceres on the Aventine.
[src:livy/aedile] It was not necessary to hold the aedilate as part of the cursus honorum; however, if held, by the middle and late republic it usually was held after the plebeian tribunate and before the praetorship.
[src:livy/aedile] Customarily, though not entirely observed by the late republic, two years had to elapse between the holding of the aedilate and the praetorship.
[src:livy/aedile] One of the main responsibilities of the aediles was management of Rome's marketplaces.
[src:livy/aedile] This included a responsibility to ensure the availability of grain and tolerable prices.
[src:livy/aedile] Aediles managed markets by promulgating an edict specifying the Rome's commercial law and regulations observed therein, while also providing men to ensure the proper enforcement of those rules.
[src:livy/aedile] Aediles also possessed a general *cura urbis*.
[src:livy/aedile] This entailed caring for the condition of streets and public buildings (such as basilicas and temples).
[src:livy/aedile] At times this could also include the construction of new buildings, such as the erection of shops on the Tiber and a porticus by the aedilican pairs of 193 and 192 BC.
[src:livy/aedile] Aediles also supervised more junior city magistrates such as the *triumviri capitales* or *nocturni*, who were part of the minor *vigintisexviri*, in their law enforcement duties.
[src:livy/aedile] Both curule and plebeian aediles possessed the power to prosecute by *iudicium populi* before the tribal assembly.
[src:livy/aedile] The offences that aediles could prosecute were essentially unlimited, with attested aedilican prosecutorial jurisdiction over *provocatio* (violation of citizen appeal rights), *vis* (public violence), tax evasion, usury, *veneficia* (witchcraft), and *stuprum* (sexual assault).
[src:livy/aedile] These judicial powers were exercised without *imperium* and also included the authority to issue summary corporal punishments.
[src:livy/aedile] This prosecutorial power also entailed the ability to assess fines from offenders, which were often used to defray costs incurred in the upkeep of the city.
[src:livy/aedile] Indeed, aedilician fines collected from usurers or illegal graziers, are attested to have been used temple construction and games.
[src:livy/aedile] However, many of the costs incurred were also paid for by the officeholders: this was especially the case with games which, when splendid, could win the man who paid for them substantial popularity with the voters.
[src:livy/aedile] This was recognised by 182 BC, when Tiberius Gracchus spent so much as curule aedile on games that legislation was passed in 179 to put a cap on expenditures.
[src:livy/aedile] The annalistic tradition suggests that the first aediles at Rome were the plebeian pair, created as assistants to the plebeian tribunes with judicial powers in 494 BC.
[src:livy/aedile] Livy also suggests that these first plebeian aediles were sacrosanct, like the tribunes, but this has been doubted.
[src:livy/aedile] Some scholars have also suggested that the plebeian aediles first emerged as priests of the goddess Ceres but there is no ancient evidence of this.
[src:livy/aedile] The curule aediles, in the annalistic tradition, were created in the Licinio-Sextian settlement from 367 BC: plebeians being eligible for the consulship and the consular tribunate suppressed, a praetorship along with two curule aediles were added.
[src:livy/aedile] Large parts of this tradition, which place the impulse for these reforms in the conflict between patricians and plebeians, have been doubted; the reforms before 367 may instead have largely reflected the city-state's then need for more specialised governance.
[src:livy/aedile] If the curule aedilate was intended to be exclusive to the patricians, this was quickly dropped.
[src:livy/aedile] Annalistic accounts of a compromise where alternating years had plebeian and patrician pairs as curule aedile, if at all accurate, did not reflect late republican practice which saw no such alternation.
[src:livy/aedile] The dictator Julius Caesar introduced two more aediles in 44 BC.
[src:livy/aedile] They may have been entrusted with care for the city's grain supply, the *ludi Cereales*, or both.
[src:livy/aedile] If these new aediles had responsibilities for the grain supply, their powers over it were likely stripped in 22 BC, when Augustus assumed responsibility over that matter.
[src:livy/aedile] The two *aediles Cereales*, however, were not disestablished; they likely were instead reassigned to other customary aedilician tasks.
[src:livy/aedile] The emergence of huge building projects during the triumviral period, which continued into the early empire under Augustus, tended against the continued relevance of the aediles.
[src:livy/aedile] The expense of holding the office, along with the few political benefits, had by 33 BC made it something to avoid.
[src:livy/aedile] In the years after Agrippa's aedilate, however, many of the customary maintenance functions of temples, aqueducts, and roads were assigned to the emperor in the name of the senate rather than kept with the annual aediles.
[src:livy/aedile] Most of the aedilician responsibilities for public order were also stripped from the period after 44 BC, though some powers over public markets (especially the sale of goods) and jurisdiction over sumptuary laws was retained.
[src:livy/aedile] Other cities in Italy also had their own aediles and they were also a standard feature of Roman *municipia*.
[src:livy/aedile] *Municipia* were commonly run by a board of four magistrates: the town's chief magistrates, the *duoviri* with two *aediles*.
[src:livy/aedile] This arrangement was common in attested colonies in Spain, but not all municipalities necessarily followed such a division.
[src:livy/aedile] It was likely that, in some towns, there was a senior college of *quattorviri* assisted with two *aediles*.
[src:livy/aedile] Elections for these positions were generally conducted in similar form to Roman republican elections, with the town's citizens divided into voting *curiae* and the victors decided by those *curiae*.
[src:livy/aedile] Candidates were also regulated by law, excluding those with dishonourable professions or reputations and requiring sureties to be posted for performance of duties.
[src:livy/aedile] Even as elections for the aedilate at Rome came under the control of the emperors, they continued to be contested at the local level.
[src:livy/aedile] At Pompeii, for example, there has been discovered graffiti of campaign messages for municipal elections to the municipal aedilate.
[src:livy/aedile] Other cities that had aediles include Agrigentum in Sicily and Corinth, at the time a Roman colony, in Greece.
[src:livy/aedile] These municipal aediles were generally put in charge of similar tasks to those of the republican aediles at Rome: supervising road maintenance, public buildings, public markets, and night watches.
[src:livy/aedile] Some towns also elected municipal quaestors, generally more junior than the aediles, to assist in these tasks but it is not clear that all towns had such a magistracy.
[src:livy/aedile] Municipal aediles were also normally inducted into the town's council (*curia* or *ordo decurionum*), either by virtue of having held office or by wealth.
[src:livy/aedile] There are few attested difficulties in filling these municipal offices until the late second century AD, when complaints about the personal expense of holding these offices – which were paid out of the officeholder's pocket – become more common.
[src:livy/aedile] The municipal office starts to disappear, probably after having been stripped of decision-making powers while retaining a rump notary function, in the fifth century AD.
[src:livy/aedile] Not all magistrates by the name "aedile" necessarily had similar duties, however.
[src:livy/aedile] Cities within the Roman empire may have adopted Roman terms for magistrates but assigned them different duties or simply assigned the name to a preexisting local magistracy.
[src:livy/aedile] Aediles, for example, appear as moneyers in Saguntum and other Spanish towns in the 1st century BC.
[src:livy/aedile] Localities with privileged status (such as *municipia* or *colonia*) likely reformed their local constitutions to conform with more Roman practices.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] He once taught Jerome, an early Christian Church father who is most known for his translation of the Bible into Latin, known as the Latin Vulgate.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] Newer revisions of the Vulgate are still in common use by the Catholic Church.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] Donatus was a proponent of an early system of punctuation, consisting of dots placed in three successively higher positions to indicate successively longer pauses, roughly equivalent to the modern comma, colon, and full stop.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] This system remained current through the seventh century, when a more refined system created by Isidore of Seville gained prominence.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] In "About Comedy and Tragedy" in his Commentary on Terence, Donatus was the first person known to document the system whereby a play is made up of three separate parts: protasis, epitasis, and catastrophe.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] Aelius Donatus should not be confused with Tiberius Claudius Donatus, also the author of a commentary (*Interpretationes*) on the *Aeneid*, who lived about 50 years later.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] During the Renaissance, Donatus's *Vita Vergili* is often collected in anthologies of ancient literature.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] The humanists had interpolated other materials into the *Vita Vergili* to add details and fill in gaps, and these interpolations are collectively called *Donatus auctus* ["the augmented Donatus"].
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] *Donatus auctus* was added some time around 1426–37, between the first and second redactions of the *De scriptoribus illustribus latinae linguae* ["On Famous Writers of the Latin Language"] of Sicco Polenton, and it became the standard account of Virgil's life up until the 18th century.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] The text and translation is found in Ziolkowski and Putnam (2008: II.A.37, 345–69), with italics for the *Donatus auctus* and non-italics for *Vita Vergili*.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] See for an evolutionary tree for all the versions of *Vita Vergili*.
[src:livy/aelius-donatus] This *Vita* depicted Vergil as a wise scholar and expert in science, while disregarding the anecdotes portraying Vergil as a magician, which were added during the medieval period in other *Vita*.
[src:livy/livy] Livy was born in Patavium in northern Italy, now modern Padua, probably in 59 BC.
[src:livy/livy] At the time of his birth, his home city of Patavium was the second wealthiest on the Italian peninsula, and the largest in the province of Cisalpine Gaul (northern Italy).
[src:livy/livy] Cisalpine Gaul was merged into Italy proper during his lifetime and its inhabitants were given Roman citizenship by Julius Caesar.
[src:livy/livy] In his works, Livy often expressed his deep affection and pride for Patavium, and the city was well known for its conservative values in morality and politics.
[src:livy/livy] Livy's teenage years were during the 40s BC, a period of civil wars throughout the Roman world.
[src:livy/livy] The governor of Cisalpine Gaul at the time, Asinius Pollio, tried to sway Patavium into supporting Marcus Antonius (Mark Antony), the leader of one of the warring factions during Caesar's civil war (49–45 BC).
[src:livy/livy] The wealthy citizens of Patavium refused to contribute money and arms to Asinius Pollio, and went into hiding.
[src:livy/livy] Pollio then attempted to bribe the slaves of those wealthy citizens to expose the whereabouts of their masters; his bribery failed, and the citizens instead pledged their allegiance to the Senate.
[src:livy/livy] It is therefore likely that the Roman civil wars prevented Livy from pursuing a higher education in Rome or going on a tour of Greece, which was common for adolescent males of the nobility at the time.
[src:livy/livy] Many years later, Asinius Pollio derisively commented on Livy's "patavinity", saying that Livy's Latin showed certain "provincialisms" frowned upon in Rome.
[src:livy/livy] Pollio's remarks may have been the result of negative feelings he harboured toward the city of Patavium from his experiences there during the civil wars.
[src:livy/livy] Livy likely went to Rome in the 30s BC, and it is probable that he spent a large amount of time in the city after this, although it may not have been his primary residence.
[src:livy/livy] During his time in Rome, he was never a senator nor held a government position.
[src:livy/livy] His writings contain elementary mistakes on military matters, indicating that he probably never served in the Roman army.
[src:livy/livy] However, he was educated in philosophy and rhetoric.
[src:livy/livy] It seems that Livy had the financial resources and means to live an independent life, though the origin of that wealth is unknown.
[src:livy/livy] He devoted a large part of his life to his writings, which he was able to do because of his financial freedom.
[src:livy/livy] Livy was known to give recitations to small audiences, but he was not heard of to engage in declamation, then a common pastime.
[src:livy/livy] He was familiar with the emperor Augustus and the imperial family.
[src:livy/livy] Augustus was considered by later Romans to have been the greatest Roman emperor, benefiting Livy's reputation long after his death.
[src:livy/livy] Suetonius described how Livy encouraged the future emperor Claudius, who was born in 10 BC, to write historiographical works during his childhood.
[src:livy/livy] Livy's most famous work was his history of Rome.
[src:livy/livy] In it he narrates a complete history of the city of Rome, from its foundation to the death of Augustus.
[src:livy/livy] Because he was writing under the reign of Augustus, Livy's history emphasizes the great triumphs of Rome.
[src:livy/livy] He wrote his history with embellished accounts of Roman heroism in order to promote the new type of government implemented by Augustus when he became emperor.
[src:livy/livy] Livy was married and had at least one daughter and one son.
[src:livy/livy] He also produced other works, including an essay in the form of a letter to his son, and numerous dialogues, most likely modelled on similar works by Cicero.
[src:livy/livy] One of his sons wrote a book on geography and a daughter married Lucius Magius, a rhetorician.
[src:livy/livy] Titus Livius died at his home city of Patavium in AD 17.
[src:livy/livy] The tombstone of Livy and his wife might have been found in Padua.
[src:livy/livy] Livy's only surviving work is commonly known as *History of Rome* (or *Ab Urbe Condita*, 'From the Founding of the City').
[src:livy/livy] Together with Polybius it is considered one of the main accounts of the Second Punic War.
[src:livy/livy] When he began this work he was already past his youth, probably 33; presumably, events in his life prior to that time had led to his intense activity as a historian.
[src:livy/livy] He continued working on it until he left Rome for Padua in his old age, probably in the reign of Tiberius after the death of Augustus.
[src:livy/livy] Seneca the Younger says he was an orator and philosopher and had written some historical treatises in those fields.
[src:livy/livy] Livy's *History of Rome* was in high demand from the time it was published and remained so during the early years of the empire.
[src:livy/livy] Pliny the Younger reported that Livy's celebrity was so widespread, a man from Cádiz travelled to Rome and back for the sole purpose of meeting him.
[src:livy/livy] Livy's work was a source for the later works of Aurelius Victor, Cassiodorus, Eutropius, Festus, Florus, Granius Licinianus and Orosius.
[src:livy/livy] Julius Obsequens used Livy, or a source with access to Livy, to compose his *De Prodigiis*, an account of supernatural events in Rome from the consulship of Scipio and Laelius to that of Paulus Fabius and Quintus Aelius.
[src:livy/livy] Livy wrote during the reign of Augustus, who came to power after a civil war with generals and consuls claiming to be defending the Roman Republic, such as Pompey.
[src:livy/livy] To clarify his status, the victor of the civil war, Octavian Caesar, had wanted to take the title *Romulus* (the first king of Rome) but in the end accepted the senate proposal of *Augustus*.
[src:livy/livy] Rather than abolishing the republic, he adapted it and its institutions to imperial rule.
[src:livy/livy] The historian Tacitus, writing about a century after Livy's time, described the Emperor Augustus as his friend.
[src:livy/livy] Livy's reasons for returning to Padua after the death of Augustus (if he did) are unclear, but the circumstances of Tiberius's reign certainly allow for speculation.
[src:livy/livy] During the Middle Ages, due to the length of the work, the literate class was already reading summaries rather than the work itself, which was tedious to copy, expensive, and required a lot of storage space.
[src:livy/livy] It must have been during this period, if not before, that manuscripts began to be lost without replacement.
[src:livy/livy] The Renaissance was a time of intense revival; the population discovered that Livy's work was being lost and large amounts of money changed hands in the rush to collect Livian manuscripts.
[src:livy/livy] The poet Beccadelli sold a country home for funding to purchase one manuscript copied by Poggio.
[src:livy/livy] Petrarch and Pope Nicholas V launched a search for the now missing books.
[src:livy/livy] Laurentius Valla published an amended text initiating the field of Livy scholarship.
[src:livy/livy] Dante speaks highly of him in his poetry, and Francis I of France commissioned extensive artwork treating Livian themes; Niccolò Machiavelli's work on republics, the *Discourses on Livy*, is presented as a commentary on the *History of Rome*.
[src:livy/livy] Walter Scott reports in *Waverley* (1814) as an historical fact that a Scotsman involved in the first Jacobite uprising of 1715 was recaptured (and executed) because, having escaped, he yet lingered near the place of his captivity in "the hope of recovering his favourite *Titus Livius*".
[src:livy/livy] The authority supplying information from which possible vital data on Livy can be deduced is Eusebius of Caesarea, a bishop of the early Christian Church.
[src:livy/livy] One of his works was a summary of world history in ancient Greek, termed the *Chronikon,* dating from the early 4th century AD.
[src:livy/livy] This work was lost except for fragments (mainly excerpts), but not before it had been translated in whole and in part by various authors such as St.
[src:livy/livy] The entire work survives in two separate manuscripts, Armenian and Greek (Christesen and Martirosova-Torlone 2006).
[src:livy/livy] Eusebius' work consists of two books: the *Chronographia*, a summary of history in annalist form, and the *Chronikoi Kanones*, tables of years and events.
[src:livy/livy] Jerome translated the tables into Latin as the *Chronicon*, probably adding some information of his own from unknown sources.
[src:livy/livy] The main problem with the information given in the manuscripts is that, between them, they often give different dates for the same events or different events, do not include the same material entirely, and reformat what they do include.
[src:livy/livy] A date may be in *Ab Urbe Condita* or in Olympiads or in some other form, such as age.
[src:livy/livy] These variations may have occurred through scribal error or scribal license.
[src:livy/livy] Some material has been inserted under the aegis of Eusebius.
[src:livy/livy] The topic of manuscript variants is a large and specialized one, on which authors of works on Livy seldom care to linger.
[src:livy/livy] As a result, standard information in a standard rendition is used, which gives the impression of a standard set of dates for Livy.
[src:livy/livy] A typical presumption is of a birth in the 2nd year of the 180th Olympiad and a death in the first year of the 199th Olympiad, which are coded 180.2 and 199.1 respectively.
[src:livy/livy] All sources use the same first Olympiad, 776/775–773/772 BC by the modern calendar.
[src:livy/livy] By a complex formula (made so by the 0 reference point not falling on the border of an Olympiad), these codes correspond to 59 BC for the birth, 17 AD for the death.
[src:livy/livy] In another manuscript the birth is in 180.4, or 57 BC.
